WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:02.640
Here's a PSA to data scientists and developers.

00:00:02.640 --> 00:00:05.840
Do you ever need to get your code-based analytics into slides?

00:00:05.840 --> 00:00:07.600
Then definitely check out Quarto.

00:00:07.600 --> 00:00:10.080
Quarto is an open-source tool for technical publishing.

00:00:10.080 --> 00:00:12.480
It lets you combine code, output, and narrative,

00:00:12.480 --> 00:00:16.959
say from an exploratory analysis script or your Jupyter Notebook or R Markdown doc,

00:00:16.959 --> 00:00:21.680
and from that, publish all sorts of output, including presentations.

00:00:21.680 --> 00:00:24.959
You can convert your work into a lovely set of slides.

00:00:24.959 --> 00:00:28.799
There's nice support for PowerPoint as well as Beamer or LaTeX slides,

00:00:28.799 --> 00:00:31.520
but let me show you how it works with a Reveal.js example.

00:00:31.520 --> 00:00:33.919
You just add a little bit of YAML at the top of your doc

00:00:33.919 --> 00:00:36.000
to tell Quarto how to publish your slides,

00:00:36.000 --> 00:00:38.639
and you separate your slides using Markdown headers.

00:00:38.639 --> 00:00:41.119
There's then a ton of options to customize your slides

00:00:41.119 --> 00:00:43.119
and say and show exactly what you want.

00:00:43.119 --> 00:00:45.759
In part two, I'll run through a bunch of your options.

00:00:45.759 --> 00:00:48.959
Slide into your boss's DMs and quickly run through your analysis

00:00:48.959 --> 00:00:50.400
with these sweet Quarto slides.

00:00:51.040 --> 00:00:54.639
And follow up for more free and open-source data science content.

